#:proof{:updated-at "2026-03-09T03:15:21.199106738Z", :falsify-completed? false, :cycles [], :ledger {"C3-verify-G" #:item{:id "C3-verify-G", :label "B_{n-1}-freeness checker for candidate graph G", :status :open, :depends-on #{"C2-strategy"}, :unlocks #{"T2-single" "T1-warm" "T3-general"}, :artifact-paths []}, "T2-single" #:item{:id "T2-single", :label "Tier 2: n=50 witness (198 vertices), adjacency string output", :status :open, :depends-on #{"C3-verify-G" "C4-verify-complement"}, :unlocks #{}, :artifact-paths []}, "C4-verify-complement" #:item{:id "C4-verify-complement", :label "B_n-freeness checker for complement of G", :status :open, :depends-on #{"C2-strategy"}, :unlocks #{"T2-single" "T1-warm" "T3-general"}, :artifact-paths []}, "C2-strategy" #:item{:id "C2-strategy", :label "Construction strategy: algebraic (Paley/Cayley), random, or hybrid", :status :open, :depends-on #{"C1-structure"}, :unlocks #{"C3-verify-G" "C4-verify-complement"}, :artifact-paths [], :heuristics [{:status :active, :refs [], :recorded-at "2026-03-08T18:56:45.430391056Z", :type :analogy, :content "Paley graph for n=25 since q=49=7^2 is prime power with q=1(mod 4)", :by "claude-2"} {:status :active, :refs [], :recorded-at "2026-03-08T18:56:45.433091188Z", :type :strategy-shift, :content "SAT infeasible at scale — pivot to algebraic constructions (Cayley/Paley)", :by "claude-2"} {:status :active, :refs [], :recorded-at "2026-03-09T01:45:08.669864264Z", :type :decomposition, :content "CRITICAL TIGHTNESS: For Paley(97)+∞ with |S|=48 (QRs), expected |S ∩ N(v)| ≈ 48×48/97 ≈ 23.75. We need < 24. This is BORDERLINE — some vertices may exceed 23. The extension is at the exact boundary of feasibility. Must verify computationally.", :by "claude-2"} {:status :active, :refs [], :recorded-at "2026-03-09T01:45:08.674323200Z", :type :specialization, :content "TUNING LEVER: |S| is adjustable. |S|=47 gives expected intersection ≈ 23.2 (more room for B_24-freeness) and complement degree 50 with expected complement intersection ≈ 24.7 < 25 (room for B_25-freeness). |S|=47 may be better than the standard |S|=48.", :by "claude-2"} {:status :active, :refs [], :recorded-at "2026-03-09T02:48:56.309920599Z", :type :strategy-shift, :content "Extended Paley S=QR REFUTED (twin obstruction). Cayley on Z_98 is now primary path: avoids extension entirely, works on correct vertex count. Codex should search for connection set C with max common neighbors < 24 and complement < 25.", :by "claude-2"} {:status :active, :refs [], :recorded-at "2026-03-09T02:54:31.382561930Z", :type :decomposition, :content "APPROACH EVAL: Optimized extension (approach 3) has feasibility window but uniform Paley pressure may block. Cayley Z_98 (approach 2) preferred: symmetric vertices, smaller effective search space (C(48,24) vs C(97,48)), rich subgroup structure (Z_2 x Z_49). QR(97) embed is natural first candidate.", :by "claude-2"} {:status :active, :refs [], :recorded-at "2026-03-09T03:15:21.198946375Z", :type :strategy-shift, :content "ALL construction approaches failed. Extended Paley impossible (any S). Cayley Z_98 failed (SA best CN=26, target 23). No SRG(98,k,<=23,mu) exists. General graph SA converging slowly. STRATEGIC PIVOT: may need non-constructive proof (Ramsey goodness, LLL, regularity lemma) rather than explicit witness.", :by "claude-2"}], :conjectures [{:id "H-C2-cayley-qr-embed", :hypothesis "QR(97) embedded as connection set in Z_98 gives valid Ramsey witness. Cayley(Z_98, QR(97)) should have max common neighbors < 24 (B_24-free) and complement max CN < 25 (B_25-free), since Paley(97) has lambda=23 and the extra vertex is absorbed into the cyclic structure.", :status :refuted, :tests [{:method "direct computation", :outcome :refuted, :tested-at "2026-03-09T03:15:21.052868681Z", :params {:connection-set "QR(97) in Z_98", :max-G-CN 27, :max-comp-CN 28, :issue "QR(97) not symmetric mod 98"}, :evidence-ref "QR(97) symmetric mod 97 not mod 98. G-edge max CN=27 (need <24). SA search also failed: best score 5 (CN=26).", :agent "claude-2"}], :refinements [], :created-at "2026-03-09T02:54:31.221460225Z"}]}, "C1-structure" #:item{:id "C1-structure", :label "Characterize B_k-freeness: max common-edge neighborhoods in G", :status :open, :depends-on #{"F2-literature"}, :unlocks #{"C2-strategy"}, :artifact-paths [], :heuristics [{:status :active, :refs [], :recorded-at "2026-03-09T01:41:49.684885534Z", :type :decomposition, :content "B_k-freeness reduces to: for every edge uv, |N(u) ∩ N(v)| < k. In Paley(q) (strongly regular), λ = (q-5)/4 is the EXACT common-neighbor count for all edges. So Paley(q) is B_k-free iff (q-5)/4 < k, i.e., q < 4k+5.", :by "claude-2"} {:status :active, :refs [], :recorded-at "2026-03-09T01:41:49.688686800Z", :type :specialization, :content "For q=4n-3 (prime ≡ 1 mod 4): Paley(q) has λ=(4n-8)/4=n-2. B_{n-1}-freeness needs λ < n-1. Since n-2 < n-1: ✓. Complement (self-complementary, same λ): B_n-freeness needs λ < n. Since n-2 < n: ✓. So Paley(4n-3) IS the right witness — on q vertices, not q+1.", :by "claude-2"} {:status :active, :refs [], :recorded-at "2026-03-09T02:48:47.680542453Z", :type :dead-end, :content "S=QR fails: vertex 0 and inf are twins (identical neighborhoods). Complement edge (0,inf) has 48 common neighbors. Swapping one QR for NR only reduces by 1. Need different approach.", :by "claude-2"} {:status :active, :refs [], :recorded-at "2026-03-09T02:54:31.413167396Z", :type :dead-end, :content "Extension approach is structurally fragile: ANY adjacency set S for inf creates an asymmetric vertex. Twin obstruction (S=QR) is the extreme case but even perturbed S faces uniform pressure from Paley regularity. The extension adds 1 vertex but breaks the uniform structure that makes Paley work.", :by "claude-2"} {:status :active, :refs [], :recorded-at "2026-03-09T02:55:05.017069775Z", :type :dead-end, :content "Extension approach structurally fragile: ANY S for inf creates asymmetric vertex. Twin obstruction is extreme case but even perturbed S faces uniform Paley pressure. Extension adds 1 vertex but breaks the uniformity that makes Paley work.", :by "claude-2"} {:status :active, :refs [], :recorded-at "2026-03-09T03:15:21.166753125Z", :type :dead-end, :content "IMPOSSIBILITY PROOF: Paley(97)+inf extension impossible for ANY S. Constraint 1: S independent in Paley (alpha<=6). Constraint 2: complement needs |S cap (v+NR)| >= 24 for all v not in S. Since |S|<=6 < 24, jointly unsatisfiable. Generalizes to all n >= 3.", :by "claude-2"}], :conjectures [{:id "H-C1-extended-paley", :hypothesis "Extended Paley construction: Paley(q) + one vertex ∞ adjacent to all QRs. The new vertex ∞ has degree (q-1)/2 and common-neighbor count with each neighbor ≈ (q-5)/4 = n-2. Since n-2 < n-1, the extended graph should be B_{n-1}-free. But exact counts vary per vertex — needs computational verification for q=97 (n=25) and q=197 (n=50).", :status :refuted, :tests [{:method "exact analysis", :outcome :refuted, :tested-at "2026-03-09T02:48:42.974063473Z", :params {:construction "Paley97+QR", :issue "twin-obstruction"}, :evidence-ref "vertex 0 and inf are twins: complement edge (0,inf) has 48 common neighbors, violating B25-freeness. All other complement edges OK (24 < 25).", :agent "claude-2"}], :refinements [], :created-at "2026-03-09T01:41:49.691768695Z"} {:id "H-C1-cayley-alternative", :hypothesis "Alternative: Cayley graph on Z_{4n-2} with connection set C = {c : c is QR mod p for some auxiliary prime p dividing 4n-2, or c satisfies a quadratic criterion}. Avoids the extension problem entirely by working on the right number of vertices from the start.", :status :refuted, :tests [{:method "SA search + SRG analysis", :outcome :refuted, :tested-at "2026-03-09T03:15:21.137279836Z", :params {:group "Z_98", :best-score 5, :best-max-G 26, :issue "No srg(98,k,<=23,mu) exists; search failed"}, :evidence-ref "20 SA restarts x 50K steps, best CN=26. SRG(98,k,lambda,mu) impossible: 97 prime forces 97|k or 97|mu, no solutions with lambda<=23.", :agent "claude-2"}], :refinements [], :created-at "2026-03-09T01:41:49.695595651Z"}]}, "F2-literature" #:item{:id "F2-literature", :label "Literature search: existing constructions or impossibility results for book graph Ramsey", :status :open, :depends-on #{"F1-opposite"}, :unlocks #{"C1-structure"}, :artifact-paths [], :conjectures [{:id "H-F2-goodness", :hypothesis "Book graphs B_n are Ramsey-good: R(B_n, K_m) = (n-1)(m-1)+1 for m sufficiently large relative to n. Established by Nikiforov-Rousseau (2005). This tells us the diagonal/mixed cases are well-behaved but does not directly give R(B_{n-1}, B_n).", :status :untested, :tests [], :refinements [], :created-at "2026-03-09T01:39:09.432510892Z"} {:id "H-F2-offbyone", :hypothesis "Paley(q) gives q vertices but we need 4n-2 vertices. For n=25: q=97 gives 97 vertices but we need 98. For n=50: q=197 but need 198. The standard Paley construction is one vertex short. Either (a) there exists a prime power q=4n-2 ≡ 1 (mod 4) for the specific n values, or (b) we need a modified construction (Paley + isolated vertex, or Cayley graph on Z_{4n-2}).", :status :untested, :tests [], :refinements [], :created-at "2026-03-09T01:39:09.440237814Z"}], :heuristics [{:status :active, :refs [], :recorded-at "2026-03-09T01:39:09.435557446Z", :type :related-problem, :content "Rousseau-Sheehan (1978): R(B_{n-1}, B_n) <= 4n-1. The upper bound comes from a counting argument on common neighborhoods of the shared edge. The problem asks us to show this is TIGHT by constructing a witness on 4n-2 vertices.", :by "claude-2"} {:status :active, :refs [], :recorded-at "2026-03-09T01:39:09.437767128Z", :type :analogy, :content "Paley graphs are the classical tool for Ramsey lower bounds. Paley(q) for prime power q ≡ 1 (mod 4) is self-complementary, strongly regular with parameters (q, (q-1)/2, (q-5)/4, (q-1)/4). For n=25: need 98 vertices, so q=97 (prime, 97≡1 mod 4) gives Paley(97) — a self-complementary graph on 97 vertices. One vertex short of 98. For n=50: need 198 vertices, q=197 (prime, 197≡1 mod 4) gives Paley(197) on 197 vertices. One short again.", :by "claude-2"} {:status :active, :refs [], :recorded-at "2026-03-09T01:39:09.444041549Z", :type :related-problem, :content "Small cases known: R(B_1,B_2)=7 (triangles), R(B_2,B_3)=11, R(B_3,B_4)=15 — all matching 4n-1 bound. These are the n=2,3,4 cases that our SAT confirmed. The pattern 4n-1 being tight for all small n strongly suggests a general construction exists.", :by "claude-2"} {:status :active, :refs [], :recorded-at "2026-03-09T01:39:09.446560675Z", :type :related-problem, :content "Nikiforov (2011) extended Ramsey goodness theory and showed various graph families have predictable Ramsey behavior. Key technique: bounding independence numbers and using Turán-type results. For book graphs specifically, the max-triangle-free subgraph and complement structure are the critical invariants.", :by "claude-2"}]}, "T1-warm" #:item{:id "T1-warm", :label "Tier 1: n=25 witness (98 vertices), adjacency string output", :status :open, :depends-on #{"C3-verify-G" "C4-verify-complement"}, :unlocks #{}, :artifact-paths []}, "F1-opposite" #:item{:artifact-paths [], :evidence-type :numerical, :id "F1-opposite", :heuristics [{:status :active, :refs [], :recorded-at "2026-03-08T18:56:45.424593787Z", :type :simplification, :content "Test small cases n=3,4 before tackling n=25", :by "codex"} {:status :active, :refs [], :recorded-at "2026-03-08T18:56:45.427902608Z", :type :dead-end, :content "SAT encoding infeasible for n>=5 (solver timeout)", :by "codex"} {:status :active, :refs [], :recorded-at "2026-03-08T21:30:46.238875360Z", :type :strategy-shift, :content "SAT exhausted for F1. Three manual paths: (1) probabilistic argument — show random G on 4n-2 vertices has positive probability of being B_{n-1}-free with B_n-free complement, proving witnesses exist for all n. (2) Algebraic witness for n=5 — construct G directly from Paley(17) or Cayley(Z_17), verify B_4-freeness and complement B_5-freeness by hand. (3) Close F1 as sufficiently-tested — n=3,4 witnesses confirm the pattern, SAT infeasible beyond that; transition to F2-literature and the construction path.", :by "claude-2"}], :label "Falsification attempt: evidence R(B_{n-1},B_n) < 4n-1 for some n", :status :partial, :depends-on #{}, :conjectures [{:id "H-F1", :hypothesis "There exists n such that R(B_{n-1},B_n) < 4n-1 (the Rousseau-Sheehan bound is not tight)", :status :partially-tested, :tests [{:method "SAT encoding", :outcome :refuted, :tested-at "2026-03-08T18:32:18.721341578Z", :params {:n 4, :vertices 14}, :evidence-ref "futon6:/tmp/fm001-n4.json (witness: 14-vertex graph, B_3-free, complement B_4-free)", :agent "codex"} {:method "SAT encoding", :outcome :refuted, :tested-at "2026-03-08T18:32:43.141062878Z", :params {:n 3, :vertices 10}, :evidence-ref "futon6:/tmp/fm001-n3.json", :agent "codex"} {:method "SAT encoding", :outcome :refuted, :tested-at "2026-03-08T18:32:43.144532931Z", :params {:n 4, :vertices 14}, :evidence-ref "futon6:/tmp/fm001-n4.json", :agent "codex"} {:method "SAT encoding", :outcome :inconclusive, :tested-at "2026-03-08T18:32:43.147154621Z", :params {:n 5, :vertices 18}, :evidence-ref "futon6:/tmp/FM001-n5.cnf.gz (infeasible — solver timeout)", :agent "codex"}], :refinements [], :created-at "2026-03-08T18:31:56.751057987Z"}], :unlocks #{"F2-literature"}}, "T3-general" #:item{:id "T3-general", :label "Tier 3: general algorithm for all n, <10min for n<=100", :status :open, :depends-on #{"C3-verify-G" "C4-verify-complement"}, :unlocks #{}, :artifact-paths []}}, :current-mode :FALSIFY, :problem-id "FM-001", :canonical {:statement "Given n, construct a graph G on 4n-2 vertices such that G contains no copy of B_{n-1} and the complement of G contains no copy of B_n, where B_k is the triangular book graph on k+2 vertices (k pages sharing a common K_2 edge). This witnesses R(B_{n-1}, B_n) >= 4n-1, proving the Rousseau-Sheehan upper bound sharp. Output: binary adjacency string, column-major order. Tiers: (T1) n=25, 98 vertices; (T2) n=50, 198 vertices; (T3) general algorithm for all n, under 10 minutes for n<=100.", :closure-criterion "Either (a) produce a general algorithm solving T3, or (b) solve T1 and/or T2 with explicit constructions, or (c) identify a named structural obstruction proving no general construction exists.", :statement-hash "sha256:7c1b69591e101dfd5f0a9263a15ec04c06b3331d83a67339546c33604e32c322", :version-history [{:version 0, :statement "Pending formal spec-lock. Source: epoch.ai/frontiermath/open-problems", :hash "sha256:pending-spec-lock", :changed-at "2026-02-20T00:00:00Z", :reason "Initial bootstrap from futon6 FM-001 problem state"} {:version 1, :statement "Given n, construct a graph G on 4n-2 vertices such that G contains no copy of B_{n-1} and the complement of G contains no copy of B_n, where B_k is the triangular book graph on k+2 vertices (k pages sharing a common K_2 edge). This witnesses R(B_{n-1}, B_n) >= 4n-1, proving the Rousseau-Sheehan upper bound sharp. Output: binary adjacency string, column-major order. Tiers: (T1) n=25, 98 vertices; (T2) n=50, 198 vertices; (T3) general algorithm for all n, under 10 minutes for n<=100.", :hash "sha256:7c1b69591e101dfd5f0a9263a15ec04c06b3331d83a67339546c33604e32c322", :changed-at "2026-02-21T16:56:28Z", :reason "Spec correction: actual FrontierMath problem is off-diagonal construction R(B_{n-1},B_n). Added tiers, output format, runtime constraint."}]}, :version 49, :tryharder-log [], :failed-routes []}